// A `@runtime` type erased into `any` still answers `is` by its own Neon name -- and now
// by its type *arguments* as well.
//
// `@runtime("neon_resource") opaque record Resource[T, E]` has two names: the Neon
// name `Resource` and the C symbol `neon_resource`. `Repr::Runtime` carried only the
// symbol, so `type_tag_name` had nothing to name the type with, the tag written into
// the box was the structural key, and `a is Resource` was `false` for every
// `Resource` ever erased. A record alongside it answered `true`, which is what kept
// the gap from being noticed.
//
// The negative direction is the half that proves the fix distinguishes rather than
// merely returning `true`: a `Resource` is not a `Flat`, and a `Flat` is not a
// `Resource`.
//
// This file used to assert the opposite of what it asserts now. The old rule was that a
// type tag names a *head* type: `Op::IsVariant` carried the last segment of the written
// path, so both a `Resource[i64, never]` and a `Resource[str, never]` matched
// `is Resource[i64, i64]` and the arguments were documented as arbitrary. That rule was
// not a simplification, it was unsoundness -- `is` is the guard a person writes *before*
// `as`, and an `is` that ignores arguments hands `as` a value of the wrong type. See
// erased_generic_is_checks_arguments.neon for the segfault it produced.
//
// So the arguments are now part of the answer, and this file pins that down with the same
// two instantiations it always erased side by side: `Resource[i64, never]` is not
// `Resource[str, never]`. `never` is the error type because these cleanups cannot fail;
// it is written out rather than inferred so the reader can see both arguments matter.
//
// The erased values are passed as arguments rather than bound, matching
// erased_recursive_record_keeps_its_name.neon: `let x: any = ...` currently leaks its
// box, a separate refcount bug and not the one this file is about.

use std::io;
use std::resource;

record Flat { v: i64 }

fn is_int_resource(a: any) -> bool { a is resource::Resource[i64, never] }
fn is_str_resource(a: any) -> bool { a is resource::Resource[str, never] }
fn is_flat(a: any) -> bool { a is Flat }

fn main() {
    let r = resource::new(1, (n: i64) => { null });
    let s = resource::new("payload", (n: str) => { null });

    // The original bug: both of these were `false` for every `Resource`.
    io::println("#{is_int_resource(r)}");
    io::println("#{is_str_resource(s)}");

    // The arguments are part of the type, so these are the wrong instantiations.
    io::println("#{is_str_resource(r)}");
    io::println("#{is_int_resource(s)}");

    // Distinguishing, not blanket-true.
    io::println("#{is_flat(r)}");
    io::println("#{is_int_resource(Flat { v: 2 })}");
    io::println("#{is_flat(Flat { v: 2 })}");

    try resource::release(r) catch (e) { null };
    try resource::release(s) catch (e) { null };
}
